Notes.Title: Unix Process States
Notes.Content: The slide outlines various states and events related to processes in a Unix operating system. Key states include 'Ready' where the process is prepared to run, 'Running' where it executes, 'Sleeping' indicating a waiting state for I/O, and 'Zombie' referring to a terminated process that has not yet been cleaned up. Events such as 'Swapped out' indicate memory management operations, essential for handling limited memory resources effectively.

Notes.Title: Memory Management in Unix
Notes.Content: The mention of 'Enough,' 'Not enough memory,' and 'Swapping system only' suggests the importance of memory availability in process management. The system may need to 'Swap out' processes to manage memory effectively, especially when resources are constrained. This indicates the system’s reliance on memory management strategies to maintain efficient operation under varying load conditions.
